tial selection system comprise the author's criteria: it should minimize the harmful effects of ambitious contenders for the office, promote responsible executive leadership and power, help secure an able president, ensure a legitimate accession, and provide for an appropriate amount of choice and change. Professor Ceaser finds that the present system is characterized by weak parties and candidate-centered campaigns that lead to the problems of "image" politics and demagogic leadership appeals. He therefore argues for a more republican selection system in which political parties would be strengthened to serve as a restraining force on popular authority, public opinion, and individual aspirations for executive power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical sciencezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistory. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxNominationxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aBanfield, Edward.  aBurnham, Walter Dean.  aEdelman, Murray.  aFounders.  aHamilton, Alexander.  aHess, Stephen.  aHofstadter, Richard.  aJefferson, Thomas.  aKeech, William.  aLafollette, Robert.  aMadison, James.  aNie, Norman.  aOstrogorski, Moise.  aPetrocik, John.  aPolsby, Nelson.  aRanney, Austin.  aSindler, Allan.  aSundquist, James.  aThe Federalist.  aVerba, Sidney.  aWashington, George.  aWildavsky, Aaron.  aamateurs.  acaucus system.  ademagoguery.  amixed nominating system.  athird parties.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691215907zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691215907423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691215907.j